  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and frameworks aimed at combating money laundering.  Here's a breakdown of some of the most significant ones:\n\n*   **The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations:** This is the **primary international standard** for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and the financing of proliferation of weapons of mass destruction. The FATF is an inter-governmental body that develops and promotes policies to protect the global financial system. Its 40 Recommendations are not legally binding treaties, but they are **widely adopted and implemented by member countries** (and often non-member countries as well) through national legislation and regulations. Compliance with these recommendations is crucial for countries to maintain access to the international financial system. They cover areas such as:\n\n    *   Criminalization of money laundering and terrorist financing\n    *   Customer due diligence (Know Your Customer or KYC)\n    *   Record-keeping and reporting requirements\n    *   International cooperation\n    *   Transparency of beneficial ownership\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (UNTOC):** This treaty, also known as the Palermo Convention, obligates parties to criminalize the laundering of the proceeds of a wide range of predicate offenses (i.e., crimes that generate illicit proceeds). It also promotes international cooperation in combating transnational organized crime, including money laundering.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988):** This convention addresses money laundering related to drug trafficking. It requires parties to criminalize drug-related money laundering and to cooperate in international investigations and prosecutions.\n\n*   **The Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990) and Revised Convention (2005):**  These conventions are aimed at preventing and combating money laundering and criminal finance in Europe. They cover the criminalization of money laundering, confiscation of proceeds of crime, and international cooperation. The revised version expands the scope and strengthens the mechanisms for cooperation.\n\n*   **Regional Bodies:** Many regions have established their own FATF-style regional bodies (FSRBs) that promote the implementation of the FATF Recommendations within their respective regions. Examples include:\n\n    *   Asia/Pacific Group on Money Laundering (APG)\n    *   Caribbean Financial Action Task Force (CFATF)\n    *   Council of Europe Committee of Experts on the Evaluation of Anti-Money Laundering Measures and the Financing of Terrorism (MONEYVAL)\n    *   Eastern and Southern Africa Anti-Money Laundering Group (ESAAMLG)\n    *   Eurasian Group on Combating Money Laundering and Financing of Terrorism (EAG)\n    *   Financial Action Task Force of Latin America (GAFILAT)\n    *   Intergovernmental Action Group against Money Laundering in West Africa (GIABA)\n    *   Middle East and North Africa Financial Action Task Force (MENAFATF)\n\n**Key takeaways:**\n\n*   There isn't one single \"international law\" against money laundering. Instead, there's a network of treaties, conventions, and standards.\n*   The FATF Recommendations are the most important global standard and are widely implemented.\n*   These international laws and standards require countries to criminalize money laundering, establish preventative measures (like KYC), and cooperate internationally in investigations and prosecutions.\n*   The effectiveness of these laws depends on the willingness and ability of individual countries to implement and enforce them.  There are significant variations in implementation and enforcement around the world.\n*   Non-compliance with these international standards can lead to sanctions and reputational damage for countries.\n\nIn short, the fight against money laundering is a global effort, and these international laws and frameworks are essential tools in that fight.\n",
